742
00:37:01,981 --> 00:37:11,960
Rym: You're going to go to your first meeting if you get involved in that stuff, and you're going to see a bunch of guys sitting around and one of them is going to say, "I move that we suspend Robert's Rules of Order for the remainder of this meeting.

743
00:37:12,740 --> 00:37:14,092
Rym: I'm going to say yes, and then they'll have their

744
00:37:14,112 --> 00:37:14,354
Rym: meeting.".

745
00:37:15,720 --> 00:37:22,880
Rym: Robert's Rules of Order, if you don't know, are the pretty much definitive way to run parliamentary systems.

746
00:37:23,801 --> 00:37:31,880
Rym: if you have to have a group of people who disagree and might be stupid come to some sort of agreement on something and avoid drama.

747
00:37:32,480 --> 00:37:53,637
Scott: Yet, mostly these systems are really useful in a situation where there are a few smart, no-drama people to administer the system, and most of the people are drama-crazy or stupid or who knows what, and if you just let people talk and do whatever, it'll just be people shouting over each other for hours non-stop, and you'll never get anything done, right?

748
00:37:54,200 --> 00:37:56,830
Scott: So it's how can you keep those people there?

749
00:37:56,910 --> 00:38:11,460
Scott: because it's wrong to kick them out and have them not be heard, and actually have a discussion and make decisions, right, together, while most people are fucking just trying to ruin the thing all the time.

750
00:38:11,800 --> 00:38:12,766
Rym: No, these were published in 1876.

751
00:38:12,766 --> 00:38:14,194
Rym: They've been around a while.

752
00:38:15,260 --> 00:38:19,655
