758
00:38:30,335 --> 00:38:31,580
Rym: It's parliamentary procedure.

759
00:38:31,982 --> 00:38:34,353
Rym: Anytime someone says, "I second your motion,".

760
00:38:34,393 --> 00:38:49,224
Rym: that's all Robert's Rules of Order, it behooves you to understand the basics of Robert's Rules of Order, because even if you never use them formally, knowing them will allow you to navigate these kinds of waters, if you ever find yourself in them.

761
00:38:49,927 --> 00:39:01,520
Rym: It allows you to rules-lawyer stupid people into doing what you want, and it just gives you a sort of idea of how you can get people to behave if you need some way to make them behave.

762
00:39:01,822 --> 00:39:03,719
Rym: But don't have any direct authority over that.

763
00:39:05,181 --> 00:39:34,780
Rym: So, yeah, Robert's Rules of Order, really, the main use of these, in my opinion, is not so much to get decisions to be made, but really, it's that it allows people to get decisions that are made where the people who lose, like we try to do X, we end up doing Y, the people who lose have to shut up, but more importantly, the people who lose don't necessarily take it personally because the system as a whole did it as opposed to one individual.

764
00:39:36,020 --> 00:39:39,960
Rym: Remember in 1776, the guy at the front of the room presided over everything?

765
00:39:40,361 --> 00:39:47,134
Rym: He was totally neutral, he had to be, and he was just like, "The representative from Rhode Island has moved to do X!

766
00:39:47,295 --> 00:39:47,616
Rym: Do you

767
00:39:47,817 --> 00:39:47,918
