817
00:43:53,486 --> 00:43:54,700
Rym: I could explain it, but I'm not going to.

818
00:43:55,503 --> 00:43:57,879
Rym: You can reconsider something that was already disposed of.

819
00:43:58,624 --> 00:43:59,539
Rym: You can interrupt for that.

820
00:44:00,240 --> 00:44:02,160
Rym: You can vote on a ruling by the chair.

821
00:44:02,300 --> 00:44:06,860
Rym: So if the chair, if I make a point of privilege, I'm bored.

822
00:44:07,221 --> 00:44:15,400
Rym: You make a point of order, you're offended and take personal affront at my boredom, and the chair says, yes, Rym, fuck you, you don't get to talk anymore.

823
00:44:15,761 --> 00:44:21,399
Rym: And then someone else votes to appeal the chair's decision to tell me not to talk, and then we vote.

824
00:44:22,102 --> 00:44:24,100
Rym: All of those things can be interruptions along the way.

825
00:44:24,961 --> 00:44:26,280
Rym: There's more, I'm not going to go down this one.

826
00:44:26,300 --> 00:44:28,920
Scott: I mean, there are rules of order, right?

827
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:32,580
Scott: It's ways of maintaining order when there are a bunch of opposed people.

828
00:44:32,701 --> 00:44:34,880
Rym: It doesn't get you justice, but it gets you quiet.

829
00:44:35,580 --> 00:44:37,079
Scott: That is what Robert's rules of order do.

830
00:44:37,220 --> 00:44:49,580
Scott: Right, and as long as there is some enforcement of the rules, right, where basically if anyone starts, you know, talking, who's not supposed to be talking or says something they're not supposed to say, the chair just fricking bangs the gavel and says, shut the fuck up.

831
00:44:49,740 --> 00:44:50,467
Scott: Shut the fuck up.

832
00:44:50,487 --> 00:44:51,779
Scott: You're not allowed to talk right now.

833
00:44:52,023 --> 00:44:53,040
Scott: Order, order, order.

834
00:44:53,302 --> 00:44:55,720
Scott: And then maybe a bailiff takes you out or something, right?

835
00:44:56,061 --> 00:45:07,980
Scott: So you can all have a ton of people who are really passionate or crazed or really incensed and have a lot to say, but unlike at panels at cons where they'll just yell out, you can't just yell out.

836
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:11,160
Scott: You got to maintain order in this hereto proceedings.

837
00:45:11,480 --> 00:45:22,240
Rym: Now in the RIT Anime Club, I think I forget, but I think our constitution basically said we use Robert's rules of order, but it was implied that we always went to, I think the term is informal discussion or whatever.

838
00:45:22,340 --> 00:45:46,400
Rym: Basically, and this is kind of my advice to you kids out there, because a lot of you are in high school or in college, and if you're joining clubs and getting into all this business, like high school youth group or whatever, and you're in a position to decide how your procedures work, I would recommend that regardless of what your stupid constitution says, your board should meet in private, if you can, and just talk and try to always rule by consensus.

839
00:45:46,680 --> 00:45:53,260
Rym: Talk until you have a unanimous agreement and only ever call a vote if you are sure that the vote will be unanimous.

840
00:45:53,641 --> 00:46:00,060
Scott: If you're in a situation where you need to use Robert's rules of order because there's drama crazy people, you're already in trouble because you have drama crazy people.

841
00:46:00,600 --> 00:46:02,780
Rym: So what you do is you go until unanimous.

