Rym: I don't object strongly enough to make this an issue.

848
00:46:21,742 --> 00:46:23,680
Rym: I just want to go get some food because it's Friday.

849
00:46:23,900 --> 00:46:25,719
Rym: It's like 5.30 and we've been here for an hour.

850
00:46:26,720 --> 00:46:31,800
Rym: But at the same time, we would switch to Robert's rules of order.

851
00:46:31,820 --> 00:46:44,340
Rym: if it was obvious, like if we'd been debating for a couple hours and it was obvious no consensus would be made, we would either just call a vote or formal Robert's rules of order.

852
00:46:45,221 --> 00:46:49,619
Rym: Calling a vote is basically calling the question in Robert's rules of order of fuck it, let's just vote.

853
00:46:50,302 --> 00:46:52,540
Rym: And you need to vote on if you're going to have the vote.

854
00:46:52,601 --> 00:46:53,739
Rym: and if you have the vote, then you vote.

855
00:46:56,561 --> 00:47:04,500
Rym: So the only other time you need to use Robert's rules of order, and this is when you use it from the beginning, is if there is prearranged drama.

856
00:47:05,443 --> 00:47:09,340
Scott: Like you're going into a meeting already knowing, drama is coming down.

857
00:47:10,082 --> 00:47:19,980
Rym: All right, all us smart people got together separately for the mutiny and we're like, we are going to strip the president of our club of his powers because he's a drama filled jackass.

858
00:47:21,343 --> 00:47:25,140
Rym: We are going to do it and then you show up at the meeting and he's ready to do his normal bullshit.

859
00:47:25,644 --> 00:47:28,686
Rym: and then you all look at each other and someone says, I move that.

860
00:47:28,726 --> 00:47:30,380
Rym: we begin with Robert's rules of order.

861
00:47:30,522 --> 00:47:31,600
Rym: I second, it approved.

862
00:47:32,300 --> 00:47:32,882
Rym: I move that.

863
00:47:32,903 --> 00:47:36,920
Rym: we remove Chairman Joey Jojo Shabadoo from the chair.

864
00:47:37,443 --> 00:47:37,925
Rym: I move that.

865
00:47:37,945 --> 00:47:42,520
Rym: we're that and you go through the full formal procedure from the beginning.

866
00:47:42,761 --> 00:47:46,380
Rym: That way the drama person has no point where they can say anything.

867
00:47:46,924 --> 00:47:47,595
Rym: They can't really...

868
00:47:47,880 --> 00:47:49,139
Scott: They could interrupt what they're affronted.

869
00:47:49,620 --> 00:47:55,360
Rym: They can follow all the rules, but they can't just speak their kind of drama piece.

870
00:47:55,661 --> 00:47:57,659
Rym: They get their chance to speak per the rules.

871
00:47:58,582 --> 00:48:03,660
Rym: and the thing is, usually when you're doing this, it's because you're getting rid of someone full of drama.

872
00:48:04,500 --> 00:48:09,640
Rym: They're pretty much immediately going to start yelling or crying or causing a scene.

873
00:48:09,800 --> 00:48:12,000
Scott: Well, it's rules of order, it's not rules of making a scene.

874
00:48:12,040 --> 00:48:13,619
Scott: so you're going to be in big trouble if you freak out.

875
00:48:13,940 --> 00:48:18,459
Rym: So Robert's rules of order basically let you immediately win as soon as the person freaks out.

876
00:48:18,640 --> 00:48:31,060
Scott: Exactly, that's really the fundamental thing here is that as rules of order, not only do they help you maintain order but really what they do is shut down anyone who goes out of order.

877
00:48:31,922 --> 00:48:41,759
Scott: And a lot of times when you have any emotional situations in group meetings that have some sort of power of decision making even over trivial matters like on an animated show...

878
00:48:41,940 --> 00:48:46,540
Rym: I was in multiple eboard meetings where more than one person cried during the debate.

879
00:48:47,501 --> 00:48:50,220
Scott: Yeah, and it's like really, it's just anime club and you're freaking out.

880
00:48:50,781 --> 00:48:55,279
Scott: But if people are freaking out, it basically makes it so the people who are freaking out lose.

881
00:48:56,260 --> 00:48:57,220
Scott: That's what they're on, right?

882
00:48:57,661 --> 00:49:03,299
Scott: So the people who are calm and collected, intelligent, not freaking out people, win out.

883
00:49:03,764 --> 00:49:05,220
Scott: And I think that's a pretty good system.

884
00:49:05,420 --> 00:49:06,694
Scott: I think you should be able to, you know...

885
00:49:07,300 --> 00:49:13,440
Rym: Now in most cases, very few people will use Robert's rule on their own where there's no meta authority.

886
00:49:13,601 --> 00:49:22,820
Rym: Like I found a local anime club, like just for me, I probably, you know, unless you watched our lecture on how to run an anime club, you probably don't think to write a constitution to have Robert's rules of order.

887
00:49:23,242 --> 00:49:26,820
Rym: But in that case, the rules are the full authority.

888
00:49:27,020 --> 00:49:36,359
Rym: So there's the sort of Andrew Jackson option of the chair has made its decision, fuck the chair, get out of my basement all of you, the club is done.

889
00:49:36,681 --> 00:49:37,015
Scott: That's right.

890
00:49:39,024 --> 00:49:41,839
Rym: And in that case, what I'm about to recommend doesn't really work.

891
00:49:42,241 --> 00:49:57,730
Rym: But in the case of you're in a body where you could get sued, you're in a body where there's a meta authority, like you meet at the library, you're the city council, you are the university club, and there's the club board that

892
00:49:58,011 --> 00:49:58,594
Scott: reviews

893
00:49:58,634 --> 00:50:03,660
Rym: the bullshit you do, where if you kick someone out of your club, they can cause drama for you.

894
00:50:03,780 --> 00:50:05,620
Rym: They can cause injury from outside.

895
00:50:06,082 --> 00:50:11,220
Rym: So you need to start formally and do everything we just said, not just so the drama person will lose.

896
00:50:11,300 --> 00:50:11,979
Rym: They're going to lose anyway.

897
00:50:12,722 --> 00:50:16,960
Rym: So that you have a very formal record of how it all went down.

898
00:50:17,362 --> 00:50:27,080
Rym: So when that person tries to appeal to the ombudsman, the ombudsman comes and your secretary gives them the role of what happened fully following Robert's Rules of Order.

899
00:50:27,541 --> 00:50:28,638
Rym: You've basically covered your ass.

900
00:50:29,780 --> 00:50:33,440
Rym: Robert's Rules of Order is a combination of stop drama, cover one's asses.

901
00:50:33,920 --> 00:50:34,021
Scott: Right.

902
00:50:34,101 --> 00:50:37,149
Scott: And you know, the covering ass is like, you know, it's twofold.

903
00:50:37,210 --> 00:50:41,419
Scott: It's number one, we followed these rules and that's how it turned out.

904
00:50:42,344 --> 00:50:43,420
Scott: What can you complain about?

905
00:50:43,540 --> 00:50:45,660
Scott: It was neutral and fair according to these rules.

906
00:50:45,740 --> 00:50:47,119
Scott: We played the game and I won.

907
00:50:47,780 --> 00:50:48,418
Scott: That's how it is.

908
00:50:49,760 --> 00:50:51,358
Scott: It's a very biased thing where everyone is out to get you.

909
00:50:51,920 --> 00:50:56,660
Scott: And at the same time, it's also like, look, these rules benefit the not freaking out person.

910
00:50:57,184 --> 00:50:58,440
Scott: You were the freaking out person.

911
00:50:58,520 --> 00:50:59,529
Scott: That's why you lost.

912
00:50:59,609 --> 00:51:04,040
Scott: Hey, look, third parties, the not freaking out people won out in this decision.

913
00:51:04,141 --> 00:51:05,419
Scott: That's why it's the right decision.

914
00:51:08,064 --> 00:51:10,520
Rym: Also, it's a lot like a burning wheel duel of wits suddenly.

915
00:51:11,005 --> 00:51:11,738
Scott: Oh, it sure is.

916
00:51:12,062 --> 00:51:13,418
Rym: And like you said, that's kind of fun.

917
00:51:15,464 --> 00:51:20,163
Rym: Now my sort of meta point about bringing this up is one, like I said, a lot of you listeners will probably be able to use this.

918
00:51:20,244 --> 00:51:22,280
Rym: It's learn this stuff just enough.

919
00:51:22,700 --> 00:51:24,100
Rym: Read this document for real.

920
00:51:24,462 --> 00:51:27,660
Rym: If there's drama, print it out and show it to the other non drama people.

921
00:51:27,700 --> 00:51:35,040
Scott: It's weird that it seems sort of like an adult thing, but actually I used it way more when I was younger and hardly, pretty much zero, not at all since leaving college.

922
00:51:35,100 --> 00:51:38,020
Rym: And you might feel awkward going through the motions.

923
00:51:38,180 --> 00:51:40,747
Rym: You might feel awkward like actually following the procedure.

924
00:51:41,252 --> 00:51:41,960
Rym: Just go with it.

925
00:51:42,241 --> 00:51:46,000
Rym: Just like actually try to take it seriously and just do it.

926
00:51:46,100 --> 00:51:47,780
Rym: Just be like, I move to whatever.

927
00:51:47,961 --> 00:51:50,259
Rym: I move to the fuck Scott in the ass.

928
00:51:50,680 --> 00:51:51,014
Scott: Whoa.

929
00:51:51,262 --> 00:51:51,937
Scott: I second that motion.

930
00:51:52,060 --> 00:51:53,760
Scott: You can't second your own motion.

931
00:51:54,684 --> 00:51:56,040
Scott: And I take that as an affront.

932
00:52:00,223 --> 00:52:10,138
Rym: At the same time, if you're going to go through the motions fully and formally and all this, if you need practice because you don't feel like you can kind of keep it going and you'll feel awkward, just play mafia.

933
00:52:10,983 --> 00:52:13,000
Rym: That's how the voting to kill someone works in mafia.

934
00:52:13,360 --> 00:52:16,539
Rym: You point and someone seconds, then you have a debate and then you vote.

935
00:52:17,381 --> 00:52:19,960
Rym: Mafia is just a tiny version of Robert's Rules of Order.

936
00:52:20,784 --> 00:52:27,599
Rym: In fact, I wonder how interesting mafia would be if you instituted a slightly more formal version of Robert's Rules of Order.

937
00:52:28,360 --> 00:52:32,799
Scott: No, I mean, because basically mafia, you're simulating the town council meeting the next day of who to kill.

938
00:52:32,920 --> 00:52:36,560
Scott: So of course that meeting has Robert's Rules of Order or something similar to it, right?

939
00:52:37,083 --> 00:52:37,900
Scott: It makes perfect sense.

940
00:52:38,600 --> 00:52:42,939
Scott: Thematically, you know, you're role playing that meeting in the morning, right?

941
00:52:44,003 --> 00:52:46,438
Scott: And it also works as a game mechanic because it is a game.

942
00:52:46,821 --> 00:52:51,600
Rym: But my meta point, and I got to do this earlier, is that certainly it bothers me about the US government.

943
00:52:52,320 --> 00:52:54,578
Rym: We have parliamentary procedures in...

944
00:52:54,780 --> 00:52:56,420
Scott: They're not exactly Robert's Rules of Order, though.

945
00:52:56,520 --> 00:53:01,340
Scott: Each different body makes its own crazy rules that are always crazy different and changing and whatnot.

946
00:53:01,500 --> 00:53:03,360
Rym: They're well beyond what the Constitution stipulates.

947
00:53:03,600 --> 00:53:05,200
Scott: The Congress actually has a rules committee.

948
00:53:05,320 --> 00:53:10,017
Scott: Both houses of Congress have rules committees that make up the rules for the friggin... It's crazy.

949
00:53:10,403 --> 00:53:11,099
Rym: I'm fine with that.

950
00:53:11,640 --> 00:53:15,639
Rym: What bothers me is that people break the rules.

951
00:53:16,602 --> 00:53:17,200
Rym: I don't care.

952
00:53:17,300 --> 00:53:26,194
Rym: The fact that the Congress can't just vote against the rules and then follow them a hundred percent, that they will break their own goddamn rules, the Republicans will start chanting, "USA!

953
00:53:26,657 --> 00:53:27,180
Rym: USA!"

954
00:53:27,462 --> 00:53:36,260
Rym: so that the chairman can actually pretend he didn't hear the point of order that was made because they'd broken the rules and had an illegal vote and that that shit counts.

955
00:53:37,280 --> 00:53:39,400
Rym: That's what bothers me about our government.

956
00:53:40,300 --> 00:53:43,871
Scott: Robert's Rules of Order are made by this dude, Robert, who I don't think exists.

957
00:53:43,911 --> 00:53:44,539
Scott: I think he's like Webster.

958
00:53:44,840 --> 00:53:47,240
Scott: But you pretend the fictional Robert made up these rules.

959
00:53:47,340 --> 00:53:48,920
Scott: Maybe there was a Robert at some point.

960
00:53:48,920 --> 00:53:49,640
Rym: Robert, read the Wikipedia.

961
00:53:50,185 --> 00:53:51,159
Scott: He can't still be alive.

962
00:53:51,625 --> 00:53:52,099
Rym: God, no!

963
00:53:52,300 --> 00:53:53,740
Scott: Right, so there was a guy named Robert.

964
00:53:54,220 --> 00:54:00,420
Scott: He didn't have, you know, Robert doesn't have an opinion on what anime is being shown this week, right?

965
00:54:00,440 --> 00:54:02,000
Scott: He's got no stake in that game.

966
00:54:02,441 --> 00:54:06,400
Scott: He's pretty much, the only thing Robert really cares about is will Robert come back to life?

967
00:54:06,480 --> 00:54:07,158
Scott: The answer is no.

968
00:54:07,541 --> 00:54:08,578
Scott: So he's pretty much SOL.

969
00:54:09,621 --> 00:54:13,340
Scott: So if you follow Robert's rules, they're not really benefiting one person or the other.

970
00:54:13,400 --> 00:54:22,980
Scott: But when, say, a Congress that is dominated by one party makes up rules, they are not just making up these nice fair rules like Robert's rules, right?

971
00:54:23,161 --> 00:54:25,860
Scott: They're making up rules that supposedly benefit them.

972
00:54:26,020 --> 00:54:28,820
Scott: It's like if I'm playing Puerto Rico, I'm going to change the rules.

973
00:54:29,203 --> 00:54:32,520
Scott: And if I'm playing corn, I'm going to be like, "Yeah, guys, corns were double the balloons now.

974
00:54:32,681 --> 00:54:34,913
Rym: Actually, it's worth couldn't do double the balloons because I'm the corn

975
00:54:34,934 --> 00:54:35,177
Rym: king.".

976
00:54:35,461 --> 00:54:43,140
Rym: That is fine in one sense, because one, Robert's Rules of Order kind of set up, you know, you can set up systems where changing the rules is way harder than just doing something.

977
00:54:43,440 --> 00:54:51,320
Scott: Yeah, it's true, but still, there shouldn't be a system in which changing the rules benefits one or more of the people involved in the game.

978
00:54:51,641 --> 00:54:52,400
Rym: That is a separate problem.

979
00:54:52,620 --> 00:55:00,380
Rym: What I'm getting at is that, one, the chair could be biased, but the rules have a way for people to appeal that.

980
00:55:00,780 --> 00:55:03,300
Scott: Robert's Rules do, but not these congressional rules.

981
00:55:03,941 --> 00:55:04,678
Rym: Congressional rules do, too.

982
00:55:04,881 --> 00:55:05,939
Rym: And this is what I'm getting at.

983
00:55:06,000 --> 00:55:06,897
Rym: This is what bothers me.

984
00:55:07,440 --> 00:55:10,599
Rym: They don't even follow their own goddamn rules.

985
00:55:11,242 --> 00:55:15,379
Rym: It's one thing to make the rules stacked in your favor and then win because of that.

986
00:55:16,340 --> 00:55:19,719
Rym: It's one thing to stack the rules in your favor and if you start to lose, to just cheat.

987
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:32,500
Rym: And the fact that people don't get that outraged about how we have this crazy procedure and sometimes we use it and sometimes we don't is one of the things that bothers me more than almost any other thing in American politics.

988
00:55:32,620 --> 00:55:33,500
Scott: Do you think anyone even knows?

989
00:55:34,080 --> 00:55:36,680
Scott: I mean, how many of these people even know Robert's Rules of Order exist?

990
00:55:37,662 --> 00:55:41,060
Rym: Yeah, so anyway, nerds especially, like D&D and gamer nerds.

991
00:55:41,142 --> 00:55:42,120
Scott: This is a super nerdy thing.

992
00:55:42,200 --> 00:55:47,819
Rym: You could actually just take Robert's Rules of Order and figure out what you're going to eat for dinner.

993
00:55:48,543 --> 00:55:50,120
Scott: Yeah, that's for a real decision.

994
00:55:50,200 --> 00:55:51,580
Scott: I'm saying make up a fake decision.

995
00:55:51,860 --> 00:55:54,039
Scott: Like, what's better, green or blue?

996
00:55:54,522 --> 00:55:55,320
Scott: We're going to have a meeting.

997
00:55:55,380 --> 00:55:56,066
Scott: You're the chair.

998
00:55:56,409 --> 00:55:57,540
Scott: Everyone else is just people.

999
00:55:58,529 --> 00:55:58,712
Scott: Go.

1000
00:55:58,772 --> 00:55:59,320
Scott: It's a game.

1001
00:55:59,520 --> 00:56:03,540
Rym: Point of order, I take personal affront to the fact that you even put blue in the same context.

1002
00:56:04,041 --> 00:56:04,424
Scott: I agree.

1003
00:56:05,834 --> 00:56:06,357
Scott: Recognize.

1004
00:56:08,902 --> 00:56:11,900
Rym: But there's a certain mystique about Robert's Rules of Order.

1005
00:56:12,242 --> 00:56:19,692
Rym: If you talk to old grognards who play war games, they always have the story about how their gaming club on campus was meeting in like the 70s.

1006
00:56:20,680 --> 00:56:28,579
Rym: And then the one fat dude showed up one day with a copy of Robert's Rules of Order and actually followed them and then ended up taking over the club and doing crazy crap.

1007
00:56:29,300 --> 00:56:33,939
Rym: There's a certain mystique and sort of secret power in knowing about these things.

1008
00:56:34,381 --> 00:56:44,479
Rym: So if you want to be the cool kid and you're a freshman in college and you know Robert's Rules of Order, you can be the cool kid among a certain subset of the people at your school.

1009
00:56:47,206 --> 00:56:47,653
Rym: I move.

1010
00:56:47,754 --> 00:56:48,140
Scott: I'm hungry.

1011
00:56:48,300 --> 00:56:49,200
Rym: That we go get some dinner.

